ce:section.ce:para:
Initially, different experiments were done to optimize the synthesis of N,S-CQDS. First, a mixture of CA (0.52 g) and TSC (0.68 g) were hydrothermally treated by reflux at 110 °C (Magdy et al., 2021), however, it had taken more than 24 h to synthesize the CQDS. This doesn't satisfy the green chemistry concept that is arising globally as an urgent demand. Consequently, developing another rapid, greener, and economic synthesis technique was crucial for simpler method development. Therefore, microwave-assisted synthesis was attempted. For optimizing the synthesis process, different experiments were carried out including dry and hydrothermal treatments. First, TSC (0.274 g, 3 mmol) and CA (0.192 g, 1 mmol) were mixed and finely triturated to get a fine crystalline powder mixture, then transferred into the microwave for dry pyrolysis treatment. For the second and third experiments, the previous step was repeated, and the obtained powder mixture was dissolved in 2 mL or 5 mL water, respectively. The obtained mixture was transferred into the microwave for hydrothermal treatment via microwave irradiation. It was found that the synthesis process could not be achieved by dry pyrolysis. On the other hand, hydrothermal treatment in the presence of water resulted in successful synthesis of CQDs. The higher quantum yield was obtained when using 5 mL water as a solvent. Next, microwave time has been studied from 2 to 4 minutes. It was found that 3 minutes was the optimum time as it produces the highest fluorescence quantum yield of 6.7% (Fig. 2
                        ). The procedure of synthesis is illustrated in Fig. 1B. Eventually, a comparison of the heat-assisted and microwave-assisted hydrothermal synthesis of CQDS is summarized in Table 1
                        .
